					<li class="nav-item">
						<a class="nav-link" href="/account">View Account</a>
					</li>
				</ul>
			
			<% } %>
		</nav>
		
	
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center show-name">
			<h1 class="show-h1">
				Finland
			</h1>
		</div>
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center show-lesson">
			<h5 class="show-h5">
				Lesson 11
			</h5>
		</div>
			
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<img class="show-flag" src="https://cdn.britannica.com/79/579-004-0EA4217C/Flag-Finland.jpg">
		</div>
		
		<div class='d-flex justify-content-center show-firstquickfacth4'>
			<h4>Capital: Helsinki</h4>
		</div>
		
		<div class='d-flex justify-content-center show-quickfactsh4'>
			<h4>Population: 5.5 million</h4>
		</div>
		
		<div class='d-flex justify-content-center show-quickfactsh4'>
			<h4>Gross Domestic Product (GDP): 270 billion dollars</h4>
		</div>
		
		<div class='d-flex justify-content-center show-quickfactsh4'>
			<h4>Gross Domestic Product (GDP) Per Capita: 49,000 dollars</h4>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<hr class="show-hr1">	
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1 show-map" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Finland_in_Europe.svg/1200px-Finland_in_Europe.svg.png">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Finland was first settled at the end of the last ice age, around 9000 BC. From 13th century on it became a part of Sweden. In 1809 Finland was annexed by the Russian Empire. In 1917 after the Russian Revolution, Finland was able to separate itself from the Russian Empire and eventually became a republic. Even though Finland had to fight the Russians during the second World War, it was able to maintain its independence.
			</p>
		</div>
		

		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Finland has cold winters and cool summers. Temperatures can be as cold as -5 degrees Fahrenheit in the Northern most places in the winter, and around 55 degrees in the Summer time. Northern parts of Finland also experiences no sun for 2 months in the depths of the winter, but the southern parts sees a few hours of sun in mid winters. Finland also lies in the "Land of Midnight Sun" zone. Northern parts experience no sun sets for 2 and a half months during summer months. However, southern towns have 19 hour days, only 5 hours of night.

			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://cdn.theculturetrip.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/aulangonjrvi-e1511893686207-1024x499.jpg">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>Wilderness of Finland</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		


		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Finland’s capital is Helsinki. The people of Finland are called “Finns”. Their common language is Finnish, although Swedish is the second most common language since they were an integral part of Sweden for many centuries. Finland’s currency is Euro.


			</p>
		</div>
	
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://thumbor.forbes.com/thumbor/960x0/https%3A%2F%2Fspecials-images.forbesimg.com%2Fimageserve%2F1061449382%2FAerial-view-of-Helsinki-city--Sky-and-colorful-buildings-%2F960x0.jpg%3Ffit%3Dscale">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>Helsinki, Finland</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		

		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<h3 class="show-factsh3">
				Two unique facts about Finland
			</h3>
		</div>
			
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Finn’s love their quirky festivals and competitions like cell phone throwing competitions, swamp soccer, and wife carrying championships where the husband has to carry his wife for 800 ft of obstacles like quick sand, and 3ft deep water!

			</p>
		</div>
		
		
	
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				In a remote part of northern Finland in winter you can stay over night in igloos with glass roofs and watch the Aurora Borealis!
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://image.cnbcfm.com/api/v1/image/104845265-Kakslauttanen_glass_igloo_Northern_Lights_2.jpg?v=1529476784&w=1600&h=900">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>Igloo Hotels in northern Finland</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		
		
		<% if(currentUser && currentUser.lessonsComplete.length > 1){ %>
			<% currentUser.lessonsComplete.forEach(function(lesson){ %>
				<% if(lesson == "finland"){ %>
					<% lessonComplete = true %>
					<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
						<a href="/countries" class="show-returnHomebtn btn btn-light">
							Return to Program	
						</a>
					</div>
				<% } %>
			<% }) %>
		
			<% if(lessonComplete != true) {%>
					<form action="/countries/finland/account" method="POST">
						<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
							<button class="show-incompleteLessonbtn btn btn-success">
								Complete Lesson
							</button>
						</div>
					</form>
				<% } %>
		<% } %>
		
		
		
		<% if(!currentUser) { %>
			<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
				<a href="/countries" class="show-returnHomebtn btn btn-light">
					Return to Program	
				</a>
			</div>
		<% } %>
		
		
		
		

		
	</body>
	
	
</html>